WEBVTT

1
00:00:01.030 --> 00:00:09.399
Jeff D'Andria: Let me see, anything else before I leave that point?

2
00:00:10.870 --> 00:00:21.999
Jeff D'Andria: Yeah, we'll talk through some of the things that you might want to get in there. I think it's important to know on the psychology piece, most of these computer science, kind of technical-type recruiters.

3
00:00:22.070 --> 00:00:37.219
Jeff D'Andria: weren't software engineers themselves, you know, so, for instance, personally, when I would go to career fairs around, you know, different states and little parts of Canada, when I had those 2 or 3 engineers with me at a career fair.

4
00:00:38.150 --> 00:00:52.570
Jeff D'Andria: that's when I think my hit rate was the best, because I could literally use them as the filter, and I was like, you guys, talk to the students, you look at the resumes, you put them in the yes stack, maybe stack, no stack, because I trust your opinion way more than me.

5
00:00:53.370 --> 00:01:01.900
Jeff D'Andria: But after that, if you're just applying online, and it probably is just a recruiter with no computer science background, you know, just…

6
00:01:02.230 --> 00:01:08.070
Jeff D'Andria: some… some just things to know that we really, like, want to see in there.

7
00:01:09.110 --> 00:01:21.239
Jeff D'Andria: Well, number one, if you have any previous experience where you've had the title, like software engineer, intern, whatever, that's kind of like the holy grail. Like, it's just so easy to say, yes, that's a slime dunk candidate.

8
00:01:21.350 --> 00:01:22.890
Jeff D'Andria: All good if you don't.

9
00:01:23.800 --> 00:01:26.879
Jeff D'Andria: We'll work on other strategies.

10
00:01:27.440 --> 00:01:30.330
Jeff D'Andria: But other than that, I would say things like…

11
00:01:30.760 --> 00:01:49.059
Jeff D'Andria: times you rose above the pack, you know? Like, if you were in a hackathon, and even better if you got some kind of award at a hackathon, but just that you're at a hackathon at all, right? But anytime you've kind of rose above the pack, maybe like a top 3, or you placed in something, or a selective award.

12
00:01:49.070 --> 00:01:57.230
Jeff D'Andria: Don't just put the award in there. Like, put the context. Was it out of hundreds of students? Was it out of 100?

13
00:01:57.390 --> 00:02:04.099
Jeff D'Andria: you were a top 3, like, build that context in. Those are the kind of things that recruiters are looking for to

14
00:02:04.430 --> 00:02:23.120
Jeff D'Andria: help you be one of the 5 or 10 people, say, that they put in front of a hiring manager. You gotta give us things like that. If you're an achiever, you know, it's easy to sell to a hiring manager if a student, if a candidate… God, look, this person is achieving things. One way to do that, for instance, could be

15
00:02:23.190 --> 00:02:25.409
Jeff D'Andria: See this selected achievements here?

16
00:02:25.700 --> 00:02:34.790
Jeff D'Andria: I've seen this a few times used, where someone just has… literally, I'm just gonna tease out and frame it myself as an achiever, because I'm going to call out the achievements.

17
00:02:35.390 --> 00:02:44.260
Jeff D'Andria: If we don't do that, they're just kind of… you're making me fish throughout the resume for achievements, but we could just frame ourselves that way, right?

18
00:02:45.110 --> 00:02:52.119
Jeff D'Andria: And then I'll say one more, there's so many others, but one for sure is, passion projects.

19
00:02:53.090 --> 00:03:06.099
Jeff D'Andria: I might have mentioned that before, but I've seen that across many… Microsoft and TikTok, personally. Hiring managers, if someone has a passion project on their resume, it almost becomes like an automatic first-round interview.

20
00:03:06.640 --> 00:03:11.519
Jeff D'Andria: So, those are, those are kinds of things that you might want to get, again, in this kind of

21
00:03:11.630 --> 00:03:12.770
Jeff D'Andria: Top third.

